# Desktop mode invariants

The desktop launcher (`cursor_view/desktop/`) runs the same Flask app
that terminal mode serves, but inside a native pywebview window pointed
at a random loopback port. The invariants below are the ones that are
easy to regress because they straddle the Python launcher, the embedded
webview, and the React app.

## Wait before navigating

`cursor_view/desktop/__init__.py::run_desktop` must **never** point the
window at `http://127.0.0.1:{port}/` as the `create_window(url=...)`
initial URL. The Werkzeug server runs on a daemon thread that is not
guaranteed to be accepting connections by the time pywebview navigates,
so an eager navigation flashes the embedded webview's native "site
can't be reached" frame on cold launches.

The required shape, owned by `run_desktop`:

- Create the window on the inline splash from
  `cursor_view/desktop/splash.py::splash_html()`, passed as
  `webview.create_window(html=...)`, never on the loopback URL.
- Pass a worker function to `webview.start(func, ...)` that calls
  `cursor_view/desktop/readiness.py::wait_for_server(port)` and only
  then calls `window.load_url(target_url)`. The probe runs on
  pywebview's worker thread so blocking on it cannot freeze the splash
  paint.
- A readiness timeout still navigates (best-effort) after a lazy `%s`
  warning, so the user is never stranded on the splash; the native
  startup-error dialog is a separate concern (Improvement 03).

Feed the splash as `html=`, **not** as an initial
`url="data:text/html;..."`. Chromium-based backends (notably WebView2
on Windows) block *top-level* navigation to `data:` URLs, so pywebview
resolves the payload as a relative path against the loopback origin and
the window 404s before the server is even up. The `html=` path routes
through each backend's native string-loader (WebView2
`NavigateToString`, WKWebView `loadHTMLString`, WebKitGTK `load_html`)
which has no such restriction. The same `html=`-not-`data:` rule
applies to every inline page the launcher shows, including the native
startup-error window in `cursor_view/desktop/error_window.py`.

## Startup errors go to a native window

Anything in `run_desktop` that can fail before the GUI loop starts
(`cleanup_orphan_temp_files`, `create_app`, `free_port`, `make_server`)
is wrapped in a single try/except that routes to
`cursor_view/desktop/error_window.py::show_startup_error` and exits
non-zero. `show_startup_error` runs its own `webview.start()` loop, so
it must only be called before the main `webview.start` — never from the
readiness worker. The readiness-timeout case (the main loop is already
running) instead loads `build_error_html(...)` into the existing splash
window via `window.load_html`. Both paths HTML-escape the message and
traceback (`html.escape`) before they reach the markup, so a failure
string containing `<` / `&` cannot break or inject into the page.

`wait_for_server` is stdlib-only (`urllib.request`), polls `GET /`
every 50ms with a 0.5s per-request timeout, returns `True` on the first
HTTP 200 and `False` on timeout, and stays silent on the first failed
attempt (connection-refused while the socket is still binding is the
expected cold-launch steady state). Do not swap it for `requests` or
add a heavier dependency — the stdlib-only discipline keeps the
PyInstaller bundle and its import-time cost lean, matching the
image-loading and export modules.

The splash markup is inline on purpose: it needs no disk read, ships
inside the PyInstaller bundle for free, and cannot 404 the way a
relative asset could before the server is up. Do not move it into
`cursor_view/export/vendor/` — that directory is reserved for
HTML-export third-party assets per
[`project-layout.mdc`](project-layout.mdc).
